They put salt on nukes now?

Salted nukes follow the idea of "salting the earth" where in ancient times Romans would put salt into the soil so nothing could possibly grow from once-fertile lands ever again.

Salted nukes however are more drastic, being known as "cobalt bombs" given that they rely on producing as much radioactive byproduct as possible that will also last as long as possible as well. This "salts" the earth, rendering areas uninhabitable for extended periods of time, along with wreaking havoc upon the ecosystem.

by Gonswanza » Wed Jun 08, 2022 6:47 am

The Jamesian Republic wrote:
Gonswanza wrote:Salted nukes follow the idea of "salting the earth" where in ancient times Romans would put salt into the soil so nothing could possibly grow from once-fertile lands ever again.

Salted nukes however are more drastic, being known as "cobalt bombs" given that they rely on producing as much radioactive byproduct as possible that will also last as long as possible as well. This "salts" the earth, rendering areas uninhabitable for extended periods of time, along with wreaking havoc upon the ecosystem.


I see. That’s an interesting way to do things. And by interesting I mean horrible.

"Dirty" bombs do this to a lesser extent. While a bomb is typically meant to kill through either sheer explosive force, fragments, or both (ignoring more specialized types like bunker busters) a "dirty" bomb adds radiation to the equation. When employed, a dirty bomb can contaminate an area with radioactive products despite using a conventional explosive, enabling the one deploying it to bypass the costs and difficulties of producing a nuclear weapon while also having the capacity to spread fear and injury over time through exposure to radiation and, to a much lesser extent, the more immediate effects from the blast and possible fragments.

In short, it's the ultimate terror weapon, even if it's a step down from an actual nuke, but a step above chemical agents and to some extent a biological weapon.

You ever hear of neutron bombs? They're low-yield bombs with an enhanced radiation payload, designed to disable personnel and equipment while leaving infrastructure relative intact. We even fielded some for a while in the 1980s.

There was some controversy as to whether they were any good against tanks, or not. Supposedly they could cause the depleted uranium layer in some composite armours to emit fission products that would cook the tank crew. Not a pretty way to go.

Despite the awesomeness of the concept a bunch of Euro-peaceniks said "no" so they were never deployed in Europe, which defeated the point. this is a jokemostly
